<div id="outline-container-org4acc8eb" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org4acc8eb"><a href="posts/mediacontrol.html">(2021-08-15) Regarding the 'Neo-Democracy', Media, and the Public Opinion in the United States</a></h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org4acc8eb">
<p>
The role of the media in contemporary politics forces us to ask what
kind of a world and what kind of a society we want to live in, and in
particular in what sense of democracy do we want this to be a democratic
society? Let me begin by counter-posing two different conceptions of
democracy. One conception of democracy has it that a democratic society
is one in which the public has the means to participate in some
meaningful way in the management of their own affairs and the means of
information are open and free. If you look up democracy in the
dictionary you'll get a definition something like that.
</p>
